                     <p>
                         
                        (i) Napper’s <hi rend="italic">Answer</hi> stated that <persName>
                           <surname>Royse</surname>
                        </persName>’s
                        lease did not begin until the expiring of a former lease (dated 15 March 27
                        Hen. VIII) to the same H. R. for 31 years. 
                        
                        This lease he bought from H. R.
                        He claimed to have cut no timber unlawfully, and to have erected buildings
                        at his own cost. <hi rend="italic">The Replication</hi>
                        (MM. 28 (ii)) stated that the lease of 15 March 27 Hen. VIII was void, because
                        <persName>
                           <forename>Robert</forename> 
                           <surname>King</surname>
                        </persName> was not yet
                        abbot, and that this made void also the second lease. 
                        <hi rend="italic">The Rejoinder</hi> (MM. 28 (iii)) denied this.
                        <hi rend="italic">The Depositions</hi> of the
                        witnesses for <orgName key="org_101005">Ch. Ch.</orgName> (MM. 28 (iv)) and for the defendant
                        (MM. 28 (v)) seem to show
                        that Ch. Ch. was really seeking for a decree to enable them to raise the
                        rent. (<persName>
                           <forename>John</forename> 
                           <surname>Wright</surname>
                        </persName>, burser of Ch. Ch., pointed out, and the other witnesses agreed that Church Cowley was worth £12 per
                        annum.) Emphasis is laid on the evils of the long leases and low
                        rents which had been bequeathed to them by the monasteries. e.g.
                        <persName>
                           <forename>Thomas</forename> 
                           <surname>Smyth</surname>
                        </persName> said that
                        ‘in the tyme when Doctor Ravis was first Deane of the saide
                        Colledge, the house was in such want that they were not able to pay for
                        there bred and other Commons, neither yet had they beene able to maynteyne
                        the house and Commons thereof, yf divers men had not beene with them for the
                        payment of great summes of money which they then owed for such necessaries
                        as weare for the mayntenaunce of there ordinary Commons’. (MM. 28 (iv) ff. 8 and 9.)
                        <persName>
                           <forename>Richard</forename> 
                           <surname>Rice</surname>
                        </persName> said that
                        he ‘hath knowne the said Colledge in such extremities
                        that the Deane and Chapter thereof have heretofore thought uppon a
                        dissolution of the same Colledge for a tyme’. (ib. f. 6.)
                        
                        Other witnesses
                        were for Ch. Ch., <persName>
                           <forename>Walter</forename> 
                           <surname>Parsons</surname>, a member of the College</persName>, and <persName>
                           <forename>Richard</forename> 
                           <surname>Browne</surname>, yeoman</persName>; for <persName>
                           <forename>William</forename> 
                           <surname>Napper</surname>
                        </persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>William</forename> 
                           <surname>Symonds</surname>, gentleman, of <placeName role="person" key="place_109235">Church Cowley</placeName>
                        </persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>John</forename> 
                           <surname>White</surname> of <placeName role="person" key="place_109278">Forest Hill</placeName>, labourer</persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>William</forename> 
                           <surname>Nashe</surname> of <placeName role="person" key="place_109339">Iffley</placeName>, mason</persName>.
                    </p>
